[{"type":"{{","value":[["pagebanner"],["S-amer africa default banner.jpg"]]},"\n",{"type":"'''","value":["Ladysmith"]}," is a city in the ",{"type":"[[","value":[["KwaZulu-Natal"]]}," province of ",{"type":"[[","value":[["South Africa"]]}," at the foot of the Drakensberg mountains.\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["otheruses"]]},"\n\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Understand"]},"\n",{"type":"===","value":["History"]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["Infobox"],["Famous people show up in the most unexpected places"],["Sir Winston Churchill was reporter for the London Morning Post in Ladysmith at the time of the siege and Mohandas Ghandi was a stretcher bearer for the British Forces after the siege."]]},"\nThe Anglo Boer War dominates recorded history in this area. On October 30, 1899 (",{"type":"''","value":["Mournful Monday"]},"), Boer forces started a siege on the town after British troops retreated there following their defeat at the Battle of Modderstroom. The siege lasted 118 days before British reinforcements arrived and were able to put an end to it.\n\n\nSir Winston Churchill gives a good account of the siege (as well as the Anglo Boer War in general) in his book ",{"type":"'''","value":[{"type":"[[","value":[["Special:Booksources\/9780742626386"],["London to Ladysmith via Pretoria"]]}]},".\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Get in"]},"\n",{"type":"===","value":["By car"]},"\nFollow the ",{"type":"'''","value":["N11"]}," from the ",{"type":"'''","value":["N3"]}," for about 20km.\n",{"type":"===","value":["By air"]},"\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Get around"]},"\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["See"]},"\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["Image:South Africa-Ladysmith-Sufi Mosque-01.jpg"],["thumb"],["Soofie Mosque"]]},"\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["Image:South_Africa-Ladysmith-Platrand-001.jpg"],["thumb"],["Platrand Monument"]]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"{{","value":[["see"],["name=Castor and Pollux"],["url="],["email="],["address="],["lat="],["long="],["directions=In front of the Town H